\section{Calculating the roots of $G(u)$ (equation $\mathbf{(3)}$).}
We have in $\mathbf{(3)}$:
$$G(u)= u^3-\frac{u^2}{2M}+\frac{1}{2Mb^2}$$
If we assume that the trajectory of a ray reaching the observers' plaque, has a minimum distance to the black hole (the perastion) than, equation $\mathbf{(3)}$ has the right form as it represents the (squared) derivative of the trajectory and thus the point where $G(u)$ is zero, represent extrema of $u(\phi)$. Suppose that $r= P$ is a minimum then we can write:
\begin{align*}
G(u)&= \left(u-\frac{1}{P}\right)\left(u^2+cu+d\right)\\
&= u^3+ \left(c-\frac{1}{P}\right)u^2+\left(d-c\frac{1}{P}\right)u-\frac{d}{P}
\end{align*}
and get
\begin{align*}
&\begin{cases}
c-\frac{1}{P}=-\frac{1}{2M}\\
d-c\frac{1}{P}=0\\
\frac{d}{P}=-\frac{1}{2Mb^2}
\end{cases}\\
\implies \quad &\begin{cases}
c=\frac{2M-P}{2MP}\\
d=\frac{2M-P}{2MP^2}\\
\frac{2M-P}{2MP^3}=-\frac{1}{2Mb^2}
\end{cases}\\ 
\end{align*}
From the last expression we get already an important relation:
\begin{align}
b^2= \frac{P^3}{P-2M}
\end{align}
which is what equation $\mathbf{(5)}$ should be.\footnote{there is a typo in the paper as equation $\mathbf{(5)}$ needs to be read as $b= \sqrt{\frac{P^3}{P-2M}}$}.\\
From the other equation we obtain the following quadratic expression
$$F(u)= u^2 +\frac{2M-P}{2MP}u+\frac{2M-P}{2MP^2}$$ which will generate the two other roots of $G(u)$.
As only the roots of it, are interesting we rewrite it as 
$$F(u)= 2MP^2u^2 +(2M-P)Pu+2M-P$$
The two roots are 
\begin{align*}
u_{1,2}&= \frac{(P-2M)P\pm\sqrt{8MP^2(P-2M)+(P-2M)^2P^2}}{4MP^2}\\
&= \frac{(P-2M)\pm\sqrt{8M(P-2M)+(P-2M)^2}}{4MP}\\
\end{align*}
Put $Q\equiv \sqrt{8M(P-2M)+(P-2M)^2}$ or
\begin{align*}
Q^2&= 8M(P-2M)+(P-2M)^2\\
&= (P-2M)(8M+P-2M)\\
&= (P-2M)(P+6M)
\end{align*}
Thus, we get the three roots of $G(u)$
\begin{align}
u_1= -\frac{Q-P+2M}{4MP},\quad u_2=\frac{1}{P},\quad u_3= \frac{Q+P-2M}{4MP}
\end{align}
as in equation $\mathbf{(4)}$ in the paper.
Also from $(1)$ we have 
\begin{align*}b= \sqrt{\frac{P^3}{P-2M}}\end{align*}
